take a look at `core/index.py/_cached_range` where this is all used

I think you mean  `pandas/tseries/index/_cached_range` ? Which I know about; one of the refactorings in this branch is around calling that method.

Looking at that method, this line:

```
cachedRange[startLoc:endLoc]
```

even when called with the same `startLoc` and `endLoc` returns both a different range object AND the items with the range are not the same.
so if you created a date_range twice with overlapping ranges, then you should get identical objects (e.g. Period/Timestamp), though the actual indicies would be different

@jreback That is what I meant when I was complaining about this not working:

```
f = pd.DatetimeIndex(start="2013-01", end="2013-03", freq="M")
# This fails:
assert f[0] is f[0] 
```

I _think_ that both these should be True; could be a bug

```

In [2]: f2 = pd.DatetimeIndex(start="2013-01", end="2013-03", freq="M")

In [3]: f1[0] == f2[0]
Out[3]: True

In [4]: f1[0] is f2[0]
Out[4]: False
```

@cancan101 can you trace a cache and see if it could work?

So looking at the code for `DateTimeIndex`, a scalar access to leads to:

```
return Timestamp(val, offset=self.offset, tz=self.tz)
```

`Timestamp` does have a  `__new__` method which calls up to `datetime`. I don't think there is any effort here to cache / intern.

There is a chance that slicing as opposed to reading one element will use the same objects. I can give that a try:

```

f2 = pd.DatetimeIndex(start="2013-01", end="2013-03", freq="M")[0:-1]
```

and then go from there.

It looks like numpy is not particularly helpful here with caching:

```
a = np.array([1,2,3,])
In [16]: a[0] is a[0]
Out[16]: False

In [17]: a.item(0) is a.item(0)
Out[17]: True
```
Ah, yes. That example from numpy is no good. The brackets return `numpy.int64` and the `item` returns `int`.

Timestamp boxes are created when you request an element. NumPy does the same thing with scalar values:

```
In [1]: arr = np.arange(10)

In [2]: arr[2]
Out[2]: 2

In [3]: arr[2] is arr[2]
Out[3]: False
```

@wesm That makes sense and is consistent with what I have observed. That being said, what is the point of this entire `_cached_range` infrastructure? i.e. what allocation / object creation is it attempting to avoid?

The point was to avoid the regeneration of `datetime.datetime` objects (and the slow date offset logic). At the time I was building applications in pandas in which hundreds of distinct date ranges would be created and creating a single array for each frequency and retrieving views on that was a big performance and memory usage win overall.

@wesm That totally makes sense...if that is in fact happening. In my attempts to test whether caching is actually working, I could not tell if when I slice the DateTimeIndex (i.e. the call to `cachedRange[startLoc:endLoc]`) if new objects are being created for each slice or not. All of my sttempts to prove referential equality on the items in slice failed.
